le Buddhism's disappearance in eastern India was a slow and gradual process, the Buddhist book-cult played an important role in sustaining its identity. In addition, by examining the physical traces left by later Nepalese users and the contemporary ritual use of the book in Nepal, Kim shows how human agency was critical in perpetuating and intensifying the potency of a manuscript as a sacred object throughout time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBooksxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aBuddhismxRitualsxHistoryxSouth Asia. 0aBuddhismzSouth AsiaxRitualsxHistory. 0aBuddhist illumination of books and manuscriptsxHistoryxSouth Asia. 0aBuddhist illumination of books and manuscriptszSouth AsiaxHistory. 0aManuscripts, SanskritxHistoryxSouth Asia. 0aManuscripts, SanskritzSouth AsiaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520954885.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles